  "prompt": "Which books should be preferred for legal reasoning?",
  "response": "For legal reasoning, some recommended books include:\n\n1. Core Texts:\n- \"Legal Reasoning and Legal Theory\" by Neil MacCormick\n- \"Legal Reasoning\" by Edward H. Levi\n- \"The Nature of Legal Reasoning\" by Alexander Peczenik\n\n2. Analytical Approach Books:\n- \"Legal Reasoning and Legal Theory\" by Neil MacCormick\n- \"Reasoning with Rules\" by Frederick Schauer\n- \"Legal Interpretation\" by Kent Greenawalt\n\n3. Practical Reasoning Books:\n- \"Practical Legal Methods\" by Claire Germain\n- \"Legal Problem Solving\" by Paul Brest\n- \"Critical Legal Thinking\" by Dennis Patterson\n\n4. Jurisprudence Perspectives:\n- \"The Concept of Law\" by H.L.A. Hart\n- \"Law's Empire\" by Ronald Dworkin\n- \"Legal Positivism\" by Joseph Raz\n\n5. Case Analysis Books:\n- \"Learning Legal Reasoning\" by John Delaney\n- \"Legal Analysis and Writing\" by Katherine A. Currier\n\n6. Indian Context Books:\n- \"Legal Reasoning\" by P.K. Tripathi\n- \"Legal Methods\" by Bare Act Publications\n\nThese books offer comprehensive insights into legal reasoning techniques and methodologies.",
